column1: it has never been about the credibility of women.
dr. christine blasey ford withstood an impossible degree of scrutiny to prove to the world that kavanaugh
column2: the man seeking a lifetime appointment in the supreme court (highest court in the land)
column3: had sexually assaulted her in high school.

column1: dr blasey ford is from the same elite society as brett kavanaugh. but it wasn’t enough. to america
column2: her power is only diminished by an unfortunate circumstance of gender. to be ‘credible’ as a woman is still considered less than an untrustworthy

column1: dr. blasey ford has been courageous and despite the disgusting response from the gop and many from the right
column2: she is hailed as a hero among the political left.

law professor anita hill also courageously testified during a supreme court confirmation process. she made it clear that judge clarence thomas had sexually harassed her and acted on her civic duty to tell the truth. anita hill was not considered ‘credible’
column3: nor was she embraced by the political left. she was attacked and vilified across the country. were it not for women like anita hill
column4: we would not have movements like #metoo now.

column1: we must shift our need to sacrifice certain women so that others can be empowered. this isn’t when we give up
column2: it’s when we learn and grow and do things differently.
i have no doubt. but i want to remind y’all that this does not mean we lost the fight. on the contrary
column3: the real fight is just getting started. there will always be men like kavanaugh and his enablers in the pipeline and at the end of it
column5: a powerful force of women to stop them. every time we fight

column1: i have written and rewritten this countless times in an effort to try to get something from the endless sadness
column3: and hopelessness i'm feeling. i wrote a list of injustices that this hearing has brought up
column4: but it is a list that is not fully formed. it's fragmented because one thing leads to the next and it seems endless. it feels defeating. check in on your people. this brings up a host of issues
column5: and it doesn't really seem like anything will be done about it. i read yesterday that hope is a discipline and a practice and maybe its why i'm running low on it. i don't have any jokes today.

column2: research and donate to a non-profit that is doing the work to help others. i chose @risenow.us whose founder @amandangocnguyen helped draft the sexual assault survivor's rights act in 2016 which establishes statutory rights for sexual assault survivors. you may recognize amanda from the @obeygiant ""we the future"" series
column3: which currently has a kickstarter (search: we the future: art for the classroom and beyond) whose goal is incorporating art that includes a diverse group of activists into schools so kids can see themselves reflected in media. no matter what grabs your attention from this media shitstorm
column4: there is someone out there doing the work
column5: and they can use your support.

column1: 328028;instagram;2018-09-28 23:49:42;FALSE;i feel compelled to really say something to tonight
column2: and it is a long stream of consciousness.  i love beautiful vistas and nature’s landscapes
column3: but to be honest i first found a compulsion to sports as a way to slow the circling wheel of trauma in my head. i wasn’t naturally good ever
column4: i was just trying to save myself. i see men
column5: like i’ve always seen most men even in my life
column6: doubting dr. christine ford and people like her (though i am very grateful for those attempting to change the paradigm). i see other men dumbfounded with what to say or do. i see few actively calling for change. i see the president making fun and calling doubt onto someone reporting trauma
column7: and even though i respect him very little already
column8: it hurts and illuminates the way our country sees victims. i see women spilling their sexual assault trauma just so they can make the people around them believe! statistically few survivors give false stories
column9: and the one’s reported are minuscule to the total amount of womyn assaulted. i feel compelled to say me too
column10: and the reason why i never reported my assaults? because i wouldn’t be believed. because my character would be publicly judged and questioned. she was drinking. she wanted it. all the gruesome things people say out loud. the things your parents have to hear. your community. because i feared for my mental health. because i was sure that i would lose myself in a trial each time the thought crossed my mind. so we have to speak up
column11: but i’m pissed. it feels forced
column13: but it shouldn’t be forced. i keep hearing that change is happening
column14: but when i looked at that hearing yesterday it reminded me a lot of anita hill. does change happen or does time pass
column15: and we forget? most of us women are seeing ourselves in dr. ford i think. i was way too terrified to do what she did. i still am. if you know a women

text below more or less from a usa today article.
facebook says security breach affected almost 50 million accounts
facebook discovered a security breach that allowed hackers to access information for up to 50 million user accounts. the company announced the news on friday.
facebook says this is the largest-ever security incident of its kind at the giant social network
column2: delivering another blow to public confidence in the embattled company.

column1: the extent of the massive hack – how many facebook users' were affected and how much facebook users' personal information was compromised – is not yet known.

security researchers suspect the breach affected even more people than facebook estimated. facebook would not say if the number of breached facebook accounts is likely to grow. the unidentified attackers did gain access at least to basic demographic information such as gender
column3: name or birthday that people include in their facebook profile.

column1: there is so much intensity happening all around us. on the screens
i’ve always felt pressured to move quickly through life. to push forward
column2: to go go go. my healing has been all about letting myself go at the pace my heart desires
column3: which i’ve been told is much slower than most.

column1: some people become frustrated at my slow pace. but when i go quick
column2: people seem to get way more frustrated
column3: because in those moments my outer world and inner world don’t match up
column4: and that creates a lot of suffering all around.

column1: i’m not much of a gardener. i would much rather harvest the seasons wild bounty. attuning to the uncultivated natural world... picking one berry at a time
column2: speaking to the birds as i pick... singing songs of praise and healing. that’s my flow.
if i keep moving at this pace
column3: i might not excel business wise at the rate others do
column4: but it means my authenticity triumphs over teaching from an unintegrated place.

column1: the natural world helps me trust all is happening at the pace it needs to. our country is healing by being exposed to tremendous struggle right now. so much is twisted. the best i can do is un-twist myself so when those who need my medicine come

i hope you come to my holistic pelvic health workshop this autumn @wyld_womyn. we’re all triggered right now straight back into our trauma. what we need to do is gather and show up for ourselves and each other
column2: starting fresh over and over with our relationship to ourselves. slowing down enough to tap back into our sacred sexuality. our self as our own healer

column1: #women #blacklivesmatter #lgbtrights #climatechange #cleanwater #cleanair #whatsatstake #whyididntreport #metoo #noh8 #womenshealth #roe #marchforourlives so #honey #homies :  #voteforourlives 👊🏾👊🏼👊🏽☑️ a therapist once shared this #truestory + analogy w me .

she'd had a ""client"" who was a child victim of #childabuse - he was brought 2 her office covered in bruises. when she asked him - ""did he know why he was in her office .."" his response : ""because i was a bad boy?"" therapist explained 2 me that the nature of abuse + intention of abuser is 2 blame the victim #victimshaming : manipulates victim in2 blaming themselves + #divided from emotional intelligence

thus abuser ""gets away"" w it by manipulating victim in completion of intention - victim harms themselves while ""keeping secrets "" on behalf of abuser - due 2 fear or misplaced loyalty  ie. abused kids r still loyal 2 parents ; others want to be loyal 2 friends ... all is fueled by #shame ;
she related this story 2 me bc when i told her the story of my childhood -
she said i reminded her of that little boy shouldering the task of staying loyal 2 an abusive family ;  i had 2 learn 2 sayno to abusive people + #neveragain blame myself ;
otherwise i'd go thru life allowing others to behave this way
column2: and take it upon myself to defend them ... never realizing they were harming me .... i relate this story 4 those who see themselves in it.

column1: it has served me well + i encourage victims of abuse 2 reject #victimshaming wherever it is found.

it doesn't have to be a severe form of abuse...it could be an unkindness that stays with you for days - undermining your confidence or your sense of how the world might turn out for you ... you see the unkind person is miserable ...and all they know - is to pass it on ... but i say : #passthison :  together

column1: 328110;instagram;2018-09-28 23:59:34;FALSE;in the wake of the #metoo movement i’ve had to carefully consider all the interactions i’ve had with females my entire life and i’ve come to the conclusion that i have been an aggressor and taken advantage in ways i was simply unaware of. i had not been taught the right way to treat people . i am disappointed in my inability to see this until recently. i have since been actively assessing the way i interact with females and curtailing behaviors that i now know can be interpreted as aggressive or threatening. i want to say: i have and i’m sorry. i see now and i will do my part to be one less threat to an already weary female population. i’m encouraging any of my male identifying friends to share this post. let’s make #ihaveimsorry viral and show women that there are those of us who are listening and trying to help. im not making excuses
column2: i’m not asking for forgiveness or attempting to make this about myself. i just want the women in my life to know i stand beside them and #ibeliveyou;;en;#metoo

column1: in middle school i did everything the trusted authority figures tell you to. i told a trusted adult about three instances in which a teacher inappropriately touched me. the guidance counselor asked me if my dad ever hit me and then sent me back to the classroom of my abuser.

column2: she called the school and raised hell. they did nothing. .

column1: at 12 years old i learned all the things they tell you to do don't matter because they won't believe you. they won't help you. they don't care. .
i realize now there was more we could have done but at the time it felt like no one cared but my parents.
i've never reported again. the reason why we don't say anything isn't because we were asking for it. it's because we've either tried
column2: been judged and never received justice or because we've seen how others have been treated and can't handle that same torture when we've already been victimized.

column1: as i've aged i've gotten more outspoken when someone says a nasty/ inappropriate comment or pushes past my boundaries because to borrow a line from the author lauell k. hamilton : .
i am a thriver not a survivor. ""
to my friends who are being triggered by these events i believe you. i get it. i'm here for you. remember we didn't survive
column2: we thrive and together we can get through this. together we can build a world where when we speak up
column3: we are safe. we can do better.

column1: i’ve written out my own stories of abuse multiple times and deleted them every time. there are a lot of reasons i want to share and there are a lot of reasons i don’t.

i know that i’m ready to share this much: i am a survivor. i have overcome multiple situations both in private and public where i have had to defend myself and my body against someone who felt entitled to it in some way.
the system keeps telling us it doesn’t matter. how do you challenge that system?

column1: 328196;instagram;2018-09-28 23:40:13;FALSE;"for whatever reason i decided to partake in a small piece of the media coverage of the awful shit happening in the us yesterday. i never do that. for a reason. i vote and live my life mindfully. i tune out the rest and dwell on what brings me peace and joy. i serve the world and myself better that way.
yesterday i saw dr. ford's testimony. holy shit it brought me back to being 14
column2: when my parents were out of town and i had a party
column3: and the football hero of the school was awful drunk and pushed me
column5: up against a wall and forced his tongue down my throat and suffocated me as i tried to get away. he had his arm blocking my neck and it hurt. he tried to put his other hand up my shirt. he was very drunk and very big and everyone's idol. i kicked him hard. so hard that his nasty drunk ass fell over. then i kicked him again.

column1: the words for how i felt yesterday escape me. i am grateful i kicked him so fucking hard. and grateful that i was gifted sons and not daughters. how would i survive that?
autumn is gloriously here today and as i wrote that last line a fox trotted by me. with a big fat tail🦊
sending love out to you all💗

column1: 328198;instagram;2018-09-28 23:41:07;FALSE;"graphic warning: as a sexual assault victim myself who also experienced being silenced once with my very own swimsuit bottoms.... i too thought i was going to die.  it is a horrifying experience on top of being sexually abused at the same time..... no words.  it began a life time of addiction and self destruction and dissociation.  thank god for recovery and all that encompasses it.

i’m so angry and upset right now because i see and hear folks questioning dr. ford’s brave and courageous testimony and i for one believe every word because as a survivor.... you don’t forget your perpetrator or perpetrators as in both our experiences.
folks are saying things like “dr. ford is so messed up or was”.... i am too!  it is a life sentence to be traumatized in such a manner.  also
column2: folks are making light and saying it was just grinding and groping.... thank god she had on her one piece swimsuit (wish i had) because it seems he was just too inebriated to figure out how to get it off her.  all of this being said in 2018.... imagine what folks would have said 35 years ago and that is why women like us kept secrets until much later in life when it would slip out to friend after one too many etc... best friends always believe you!  as dr. ford found ...feeling is healing and also went to therapy to help deal with her trauma.  i’m saying all of this to stress that i can’t believe how many folks dismiss this as groping and expected male behavior!?!? what i don’t understand is how kavanaugh is dead set against an fbi investigation and also how he could sit in front of god and the world and lie about never being foggy or having a blackout after drinking!?!? anyone who has ever gotten drunk or even tipsy have memory lapses.  there are so many other qualified candidates but now feel as though i’m having a sexual predator and liar voted into the highest seats in our country and it sickens me that someone that can lie that easily will be making the most important decisions for the rest of my life.  i welcome kind thoughts and banter but please be gentle as this is such a sensitive matter. #metoo #ibelieveher #loveandonlylove #sexualassaultawareness #truth #sobrietyrocks #survivor";;en;#metoo

column1: it was 25 months ago and i still remember how the room smelled like cigarettes and bruising. it took me one month to go to therapy
column2: which was induced by a friend who intervened and questioned my bizarre and reckless behavior. it took me three months to verbalize the words “rape” and “assault”. for weeks in therapy
column3: i referred to it as “the incident”. i remember the first time i told my story to a friend and how he reached for my hand. i remember how my first dates and encounters with new men after my rape made me feel insecure. i remember what it felt like when i let go of the guilt and anger i had so wrongly directed at myself. i remember what it was like to forgive myself
column4: for ever having placed the blame on me and thinking i was left broken. i wasn’t and am not broken. rapists and assailants are the ones that are broken because they feel they have jurisdiction over our bodies
column5: they feel we are property that can be stolen off a shelf. we are not a commodity and as dr. ford so bravely stated
column6: nor are we pawns. believe survivors
column7: not because we are your daughters
column13: or partners. believe us because we are people. we are individuals who deserve to be respected and valued regardless of our title or relation to any man. .

column2: this week has been extremely hard for me as it has been for plenty of survivors. although i debated on posting something so personal
column3: be it that at times i have hinted at my experience
column4: i do believe in the power of story telling. rape and violence towards womxn/femmes
column6: that perhaps in sharing our stories (if and when we want to) it shows how wide spread of a problem this is in society
column7: not just here in the states but across the world. .

column1: a naked male body registers as threatening for many women. men go
column4: a naked male body can be coupled with demands and expectations. it can be reminiscent of experiences that registered as threat
column6: or were violations. our perceptions are not stagnant. because of the repeated words “sexual assault
column9: ” the world seems less safe for women right now. even my 11 year old daughter has said she feels more afraid of men right now
column10: that she doesn’t know who to trust or what to believe. this is a very unfortunate by-product of what’s happening right now. we need men. we need each other. and we need men standing beside us as allies and advocates. white men certainly hold the power in this country. but each white man is not a power holder. and while patriarchy is the enemy
column11: men are not. most men are deeply caring. most men want to do right. most men are trying their best to hold space and figure out what’s going on. there’s a double bind being offered to them right now- “shut up
column12: sit down and listen. you’ve been talking for too long and it’s time for you hand over the mic and listen.” on the other hand
column13: “where are the men? where are your voices? why aren’t you speaking up now? why aren’t you marching? why aren’t you making calls?” you see the trap right? “don’t do anything- wait
column14: why aren’t you doing anything?” people are calling this negligence and passivity. there’s a fine line between passivity and freeze. we have to make space for advocacy
column16: and genuine apologies. men are also reviewing their pasts
column18: while a few of them are probably shaking in their boots that they may be exposed
column19: most of them are deeply questioning how they can make the wrongs right. i can tell you that we are all suffering. join me for a vision of a way out. linktree for details.

column1: 328255;instagram;2018-09-28 23:20:00;TRUE;;"our founder/ceo will be joining this wonderful panel at @hispanicizeevent la. a trialblazer in her own right sandra varona is uplifting her sisters in the industry through creating opportunities for females in more unconventional production roles.

#repost: we are so excited to announce that actress essence atkins @essence_says is joining @hispanicizeevent la to speak about a super important subject: beyond #metoo & #timesup to #whatsnext. how today's hollywood women are breaking the glass ceiling.
joining her are gabrielle carteris @gabriellecarteris president of sag-aftra
latina producers gabriela revilla lugo @gabbyrlugo and sandra varona @sendyvarona and more names tba next week! the panel will be moderated by rita garcia @theritagarcia

the #metoo and #timesup campaigns have sparked a movement putting sexual harassment and gender discrimination in hollywood center stage and have created a grand effort to counter systemic sexual harassment not just in the entertainment industry
column2: but also in industries across the country. but #whatsnext ? diverse women of power in hollywood both in front and behind the cameras discuss how together we can empower women and a new generation by taking a lead in our positions and creating change through positive representation!";en;#REPOST:

column2: we can yell at them til they change out of fear of us.

column1: or else consider the very next word they might need to hear for a possible step in a new direction (that is certainly not promised).
the cyber glass wall of intimidation changes no one.
the evangelism of any philosophy that shows up to preach but doesn’t know where you are at all - doesn’t work.
could the best bet be to keep growing as individuals with great hope for every other man and woman? showing kindness
column2: and looking for the graciously worded bridges toward one another when possible? .

column1: we think we just have to tell someone to open their eyes. that it’s that simple.
but sight is grown over a lifetime - if it’s sincere.
if change isn’t sincere then who cares. it’s worthless.

••when you hear women talking about taking down patriarchy understand it is not just about respecting women’s bodies and fairness in the work place-obviously those things are incredibly important but those should be basic fucking human rights. it’s also about the bigger systems in our culture that make the masculine way of doing things the standard-—undermining the feminine aspects of us all.

••this time of “me too” is powerful and triggering esp. for those of us that aren’t straight men. i have to turn off the radio constantly because the stories in the news from survivors that deserve to be shared also bring up flashbacks that i’ve long dealt with but don’t want to revisit. things that are too terrible to share on social media
column2: and awful hard to shake. i wish men could empathize with how much all this effects us....... how tiring it is to be on guard constantly
column3: how different it is when we are alone or outnumbered. how it feels to not be fully heard
column4: and when you do express yourself you are perceived as too emotional/sensitive/difficult/exaggerating or a complainer. how when someone is inappropriate you are expected to just take it in a stride because it happens all the damn time anyway. how in 2018 women are still fighting for their right to choose if they want to raise a child. how because of all this it is clear we are not treated as equals and never have been.

column1: ••the gentlemen in my life would never cross the line and whole heartedly believe in equality——but i ask all of you to look deeply at yourselves and your brothers and hold each other accountable
column3: even if it is uncomfortable. if you respect your mother/sister/partner then let them know you stand behind them
column4: esp. right now. if you respect women then really listen to them. take the time to be present
column5: ask for our input and be open to a different perspective. understand that there are different communication styles and stop making it all about you and they way you see the world. thank you to all the men speaking up and doing the work. power to my sisters! 💪🏼💖⚡️";;en;;;;;;0;;lyzarenee00;Lyza Renee;;0;False;16;0;0;125;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/35fa6992253627d7354064863e277174/5D08B448/t51.2885-15/e35/41785430_318792418900105_3492461135435856320_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"a storm coming in with pink lightning on the left and the sun setting on the right. symbolic of the times

column1: 328279;instagram;2018-09-28 23:05:24;FALSE;"“i am the opposite of forgiveness. i am all rage and shriek and flame.” ~ @blythebaird —————————————————————
background information: brett kavanaugh was confirmed by the senate judiciary committee today. he still needs to be confirmed by the full senate. —————————————————————
i think the worst part of it is that i am not surprised. i have seen time after time after time that this country does not care about women.
i saw it after donald trump was elected.
i saw when i was raped.
i saw it when i was raped countless times after that.
i saw it when i went to my school and told them about my abuse and they didn’t do a fucking thing.
i saw it when my rapist was elected to our student council.

i saw it when his parents called mine and told me to stop talking about my assaults because i was “making his life hard.” i saw it yesterday when a teacher turned off the testimony because “we have a lot to do today.” i saw it today on the faces of my friends.
i saw it when the silence suffocated me in every single class.
my heart aches because the men in positions of power have been informed about sexual violence
column2: heard from a survivor and decided that it didn’t matter. that they didn’t care.

column1: what message are we sending to women
column3: and people of all genders about their place in society?

column1: what message are we sending to survivors?
i don’t know how to end this post. i am shaking with anger. i am choking back tears. i am disgusted to my very core. i guess i’ll just say this:
men - as hannah gadsby would say

column1: in regards to what’s been going on in the news: i stand with survivors.
it seems most of us have our own stories of assault
column2: and seeing something so traumatizing go on display so publicly for seemingly anyone’s criticism can be incredibly draining. i’m lucky enough to have people in my life who don’t victim blame
column3: but it wasn’t always that way. hearing all of the dissenting voices towards the victim this time around
column4: i feel a lot more strong and have the strength to say ”how dare you.” i made these originally at the request of a friend
column5: but never posted them. i feel like now would be a good time. let victims tell their stories. listen to them
column6: and don’t try to automatically talk over them
column7: trying to tell them they’re wrong for whatever reason. don’t fucking talk over us. 🌸

column1: 328295;instagram;2018-09-28 23:10:40;FALSE;"i took the opportunity to share my #metoo story at the #justiceforsurvivors rally in birmingham today. (cw: sexual abuse)
dr. blasey ford's testimony inspired me to share about my own experience with sexual abuse as a high schooler. i had developed a crush on a college student at summer camp
column2: and he told me if i really loved him
column3: i would expose myself to him every evening through photos and videos. this went on for several months
column4: and i didn't tell anyone because he said he loved me
column5: and even though it started to severely impact my life
column6: i felt that the entire situation was my fault.

column1: i was very lucky-- i eventually broke down and told my parents when i realized i would not be able to end the abuse on my own. they were able to prevent him from further contact with me and made sure i could receive counseling. but the experience still haunts me
column2: as i sometimes have to sit down and ask myself if i'm doing something because i want to
column3: or because the feeling of having to subvert my own needs to earn love lingers.

column1: i share my story because i know there are others who have experienced similar traumas and i want to tell them exactly what i wanted to hear at that time: you are not alone
column3: you are not to blame for the cruelty others perpetrate in your life. you are strong whether you tell your story today
column5: or hold it in your heart for the rest of your life. that's why i chose this quote from dr. blasey ford for my sign. i needed that reminder that i am no one's pawn
column6: and neither are you. you are an autonomous human being
column9: you're capable of making the world a better place. regardless of political leanings
column10: let's listen to survivors and seek to understand. #webelieveher #noonespawn";;en;#metoo

column2: i have considered sharing the story that made me part of a number of statistics which include:

column1: one in four women in north america will be sexually assaulted in their lifetime. 80% of sexual assault is committed by someone the survivor knows. in a global/ipsos reid poll
column2: the most common reason women gave for not reporting a sexual assault to the police was feeling young and powerless (56%). forty percent of respondents said they stayed silent because of the shame they felt and 29% said they blamed themselves for the assault. *

column1: all of this is me. i still can't share  #whyididntreport because it hurts too much. it took me years to realize that just because what had happened wasn't rape
column2: it didn't make it any less traumatic or valid. that my pain was real. that i was robbed of my sense of safety and security. that this is something i will deal with for the rest of my life.

column1: the kavanaugh hearings were difficult for me and so many others. i was prepared for them to stir up certain memories
column2: but you can never predict what will flow through once the flood gates open. kavanaugh scared me. watching him yell in anger - with utter indignance
column3: entitlement and outright beligerence - was like being on the receiving end of a verbal assault from my ex boyfriend. hearing him brush aside obvious alcoholic behavior as normal behavior that everyone does felt the same. my ex was a vicious alcoholic. i developed problems with alcohol to cope with our relationship (problems that outlived the relationship that i only began to address when i began to feel safe
column4: emotionally). i didn’t realize how much kavanaugh would make me think of the horrors of being with him. i thought of a photo from a music festival
column5: where i wore one of my favorite shirts. i had gone to the festival with other friends in an attempt to get away from him
column7: and berated me for abandoning him. he had been having stomach pains recently
column8: and there was suspicion that he may have
column10: developed alcohol disease. i was relieved. i wanted a reason for him to stop drinking
column11: even though i knew that’s not how that really works. he arrived at the festival
column12: furious with me. someone asked how his stomach was doing and he took a massive gulp of whiskey and proclaimed
column14: it’s my liver!” he glared at me
column15: and our friends looked at me
column16: as if i should do something. our interactions were verbally aggressive throughout the night and he flirted with other women
column17: so i did my best to avoid him. i was supposed to sleep in a friend’s tent
column18: but when i tried i was kicked out because they were having sex. i was offered a pillow and told i could sleep next to the tent. i woke up to a man on top of me
column19: attempting to remove my clothes. i scrambled away
column21: but just drunk enough to move on in that moment. what else was i gonna do? i had to survive. i didn’t want to
column22: but i went searching for my ex. i found him drunk at a fire

column1: 328370;instagram;2018-09-28 22:54:06;FALSE;watching doctor ford’s bravery and humility the last few days has really influenced me. i have had a terrible last few days. let me tell you why. i am so tired. i am exhausted. this society is so broken. watching everything she had to go through in reporting her story was so familiar to me and brought up so many memories
column3: and feelings that i have been at a loss. i am a survivor of sexual assault. something i have
column5: waited to express on social media until now. i came forward and i told my story to an accredited university who convinced me that they had my best interests at heart. i saw virtually nothing done about what happened to me
column6: although my assailant was found in violation of the sexual assault policy held by the university. i have watched people turn against me
column9: tell me that what happened to me wasn’t “that bad.” i’ve had people tell me they would “stay out of it” because they didn’t want to pick sides. these same people are now supporting doctor ford
column12: i of course will believe you if you come forward. if you have that bravery and that tenacity
column13: i applaud you. there will be people who will stick by you through this and you will make it. but if you’re gonna come forward you better be prepared for nothing to happen. you better be prepared for your attacker to get nothing more than a slap on the wrist even though you have witnesses to corroborate your story. you better be ready to get put on trial even though you did nothing wrong. you better be prepared for some of you friends to abandon you. you better be prepared to feel that feeling of dread in the pit of your stomach every time you tell your story because you are absolutely terrified that people you have known for years and who you thought loved you might not believe what you went through or might not believe what you’re saying is a “big enough deal.” i hate that. i really truly do. because no one should have to go through any of this. #ibelievesurvivors #metoo #drford #metoomovement #survivor;;en;#ibelievesurvivors

column1: 328378;instagram;2018-09-28 22:55:16;FALSE;"it is okay to not be okay.
it is okay to turn down the bluster of television noise and to quiet the world outside of your safe havens.
it is okay to share your stories out loud with the big noise of perseverance and bravery because your voices truly matter.
to the women who are strong out loud and those who are brave in silence.
to the women who are aching and afraid and reminded.
to the countless women who march and shout and share story after story of survival so that our daughters never know this pain.

column1: 328388;instagram;2018-09-28 22:31:30;FALSE;i’m not usually one to use social media as a place to voice my personal political opinions but enough is enough. since when is it more shameful to be raped than to be a rapist? some people’s opinions on this matter are apalling. there is never an excuse for sexual assault and it is a woman’s prerogative to not report her assault until she is ready and not a moment sooner. it is not a sexual assault survivors responsibility to report her abuser. full stop. no one asks to carry the burden of having been victimized & no one has to justify why they came forward when they did or why they never came forward. everyone has their reasons. & then when women do come forward and name their abuser

column1: 328401;instagram;2018-09-28 22:43:03;FALSE;"this week i’m proud of the women and men in america standing by dr. ford. i’m also sad that this is the reality and that these things happen to people. sad too that people feel the need to overpower someone else through sexual assault and rape. i could feel dr. ford trembling as she stood and gave her testimony. i believe her pain is real. poetry has been my way of expressing this kind of pain and speaking up as clearly as i can
column2: for a long time now. i wrote a poem today
column3: i think mostly in hopes that others will feel the pain a victim of sexual violence experiences so that they won’t want to ever be a part of something like that
column4: in hopes that we can come together
column6: to show that this behavior will never be tolerated. ❤️

column1: letters meant to be kept private
they’ve forgotten the definition of anonymous
a heroine from an everlasting tale
of his body on top of hers
the smell of alcohol on his breath
the voyeur cheering in the corner of the room
the music’s bass drowning out her cries for help - boom
the sweaty hand gripping her mouth
the sound of laughter in the hall
and the darkness on the street outside
to make sure she wasn’t followed
all of the women whose story you tell
all of the men who cry out in defense
we will not let your voice be quieted
no victory of theirs will be lasting or true

column1: excerpt from an article which unpacks the limited function and potential harm of celebrating the ""resilience of survivors
column2: who achieve recognition only through sharing and recycling their pain. resilience is measured against a hierarchical scale. this is how the mythology of the “perfect” harassment victim is created. the savvy and resourceful victim who most definitely wasn’t asking for it. points are detracted every time a victim’s story doesn’t add up or follow this prearranged trajectory...victims who freeze up
column5: who don’t perform resilience; they are the ones who are cross-examined only to be ultimately denied recognition. the politics of recognition is a politics that wants to see us kicking
column9: and finally witnessing. failure to perform an over-determined resilience will cost you. our descriptive energies can be taken up in the baring of the wound and not in its healing. time and time again
column10: we see resilience called upon in the service of reform...resilience myths make symbols out of survivors instead of analyzing the political realities behind what they have had to survive. behind what they shouldn’t have to survive."" source: momtaza mehri - on noise and networks

column1: 328439;instagram;2018-09-28 22:34:00;FALSE;"for those of you who still ask why i and others do not come forward for years/decades after a sexual assault and for those who don’t believe accusers who do

when we are assaulted all we could think about was getting through it and how it affected our lives in that nanosecond. we were in complete and total survival mode.  only a few years ago there was no #metoo movement to help us feel we were not alone.  the culture was one that supported the accused.  television and culture at that time taught us that it was somehow our fault for wearing the wrong clothes
column4: doing the wrong things. this message was pounded into our psyche over and over again.  therapy was still a taboo. we had nowhere to turn. all we focused on afterwards was getting through the next day
column6: and the day after that...one day at a time.  we avoided the one who assaulted us at all costs.  for many of us
column7: even avoiding them was not an option
column8: so we tuned them out mentally and separated the person who assaulted us from the person right in front of us. we buried the memories as deep as possible to protect our fragile peace and mental health.  and every time our family or friends said something in our hearing about
column9: or made a social media post about
column10: their support of men who are accused of assault/abuse or about how “boys will be boys” or how “people change/they’re a good person now
column11: ” we buried it even deeper and we become even more convinced that we will not be believed
column13: that we will be believed but no one will care.  this is why we do not come forward.  but then one day we turn on the tv
column16: or go to an event and there he is....and he is being considered for a job or is assuming a role that will have a significant impact on not only our life but the lives of others.  and we can no longer keep the memories at bay. we no longer have our fragile peace and our hard-won mental health. the experience is in our face and we are forced to relive it over and over again. and we are faced with a terrible decision.  #metoo #whyvictimsdontcomeforward";;en;#metoo

column1: how are you holding up this fine friday?
what are you up to this weekend?

i'm out of energy on every level and ready to snuggle up with this lump.  the feed is hypnotic and draining though i'm heartened by the general agreement i'm seeing amongst those i know and follow-- that people who come forward to share their stories of trauma are to be believed and respected.
i'm not sure how to reconcile the rest of the feelings-- anxiety

column3: and communicating our needs consistently to our representatives we'll see a more equitable

column1: 328453;instagram;2018-09-28 17:04:28;FALSE;i have been at a loss for words
column2: but moved by the strength of other women speaking their truth
column3: i know what i have to say: it happened to me. i am still ashamed at having been that wasted white girl
column5: who cant walk or make decisions for herself. that night
column7: someone else made a decision for me.  he took me from the party
column8: drove to another house and returned me a few hours later. i was seen being carried. the next day i found my underwear in my pocket and figured out who the guy was a few days later. i have zero recollection and was barely acquaintances with this person. i will never forget that sick feeling. was it date rape? or actual rape? or something else...? i don’t know... i was not on a date with him. i know that. i know that it was wrong. i know that everything in me wants to defend myself here and tell you about how i wasn’t “that kind of girl”. that this hadn’t happened to me before or since. but that’s not the fucking point. i attempted to press charges and gave my statement to authorities. they discouraged me from proceeding further
column10: and had been under the influence of drugs and alcohol
column11: and he was a law student from a good family. apparently he didnt even drink much that night
column13: fine to drive.... what a guy
column14: right?  who would believe me? it was soon brushed under the rug. i know i shouldn’t have been that fucked up. i know there are clearer examples of sexual abuse.. but he was wrong. i always told myself that he knew it too and was probably sorry
column15: although he never said so. i can’t say for sure how this affected me psychologically. pretty sure i’m (mostly) fine. for years
column16: my heart would race when alone with men i didn’t know
column18: waiting for the right opportunity.  some probably were. i hardly ever think of that night now and i’m sure no one else does either. least of all this nice lawyer
column20: with his nice family. if you’re out there

column1: 328456;instagram;2018-09-28 22:00:23;FALSE;"that's why we don't speak out. i decided that 2018 would be the year i stop hiding my truth. until recently only my closest friends and a few family members knew that i had been raped when i was younger. it was by someone older than me and who was in authority and i was scared to death and too embarrassed  to tell anyone. i hid it as best i could. even from myself to the point that i had forgotten about it until 2 years ago when i found out that he had died. i broke down in tears. literally! i fell in the floor and my friend had to pick me up. he thought i was upset at the fact that the man had died when in fact all of the memories and pain came back like a hurricane!! i remembered every touch
column3: & even the sound of his voice! it hit me hard but still i felt so bad that i was so happy that he was dead. this damn heart of mine gets me every time. but that forced me to finally face that pain and deal with it. i'm still healing from so many things in my life and i'm so grateful for the strength to keep going through all of it! sometimes i look myself in the mirror and say ""girl you are strong!"" i can't even believe that i'm still able to love
column5: trust (a little) & be so patient after everything i've been through. i'm still a work in process but i know that everything i've been through was not in vein.  #nomoresilence #beverlynvercher #metoo";;en;#NoMoreSilence

column1: 328531;instagram;2018-09-28 22:02:02;FALSE;"do not read the rest of this if you are sensitive to the #metoo #whyididntreport #nomeansno or any other related movement

the first time i ever had sex i was raped. i thought he was my friend. it became incredibly hard to trust after that & i spent the next three years at least convinced that sex was inherently painful & traumatic. i said no a hundred times but when my fighting acquiesced he took that as a yes. i spiraled & got kicked out of school two weeks later.

fast forward a few years & i was raped by another acquaintance at a party. he kept pulling me into the closet. i managed to struggle my way out the first few times even though he was much stronger than me. i told people there that i was uncomfortable but they were more his friends than mine & replied with “aw
column2: he’s not so bad”. afterwards they did not answer when they heard me cry for help.

column1: these are just the first few examples from when i was a teenager. i did not understand consent & internalized the shame & blame from everything. i’m 23 now & have healed a lot since then. the crazy thing is almost every woman has similar stories to these. but hopefully not my little sister
column2: because i told her that no matter what
column3: no matter how friendly or flirty she is with someone
column4: no matter how fancy of a date they take her on
column5: no matter what she has agreed to in the past
column8: no matter how aggressive or forward or entitled someone is... she does not owe them anything. ever. under any circumstances. her body is hers & hers alone. there are also times when someone is too young or too intoxicated to truly be able to make that kind of decision & that has to be respected more. we all deserve to feel safe

column1: the first time i ever had sex i was raped. i thought he was my friend. it became incredibly hard to trust after that & i spent the next three years at least convinced that sex was inherently painful & traumatic. i said no a hundred times but when my fighting acquiesced he took that as a yes. i spiraled & got kicked out of school two weeks later.

fast forward a few years & i was raped by another acquaintance at a party. he kept pulling me into the closet. i managed to struggle my way out the first few times even though he was much stronger than me. i told people there that i was uncomfortable but they were more his friends than mine & replied with “aw
column2: he’s not so bad”. afterwards they did not answer when they heard me cry for help.

column1: these are just the first few examples from when i was a teenager. i did not understand consent & internalized the shame & blame from everything. i’m 23 now & have healed a lot since then. the crazy thing is almost every woman has similar stories to these. but hopefully not my little sister
column2: because i told her that no matter what
column3: no matter how friendly or flirty she is with someone
column4: no matter how fancy of a date they take her on
column5: no matter what she has agreed to in the past
column8: no matter how aggressive or forward or entitled someone is... she does not owe them anything. ever. under any circumstances. her body is hers & hers alone. there are also times when someone is too young or too intoxicated to truly be able to make that kind of decision & that has to be respected more. we all deserve to feel safe

column1: 328538;instagram;2018-09-28 22:02:59;FALSE;"this is my rape story.  i don’t usually speak openly of politics or past trauma on my social media.  i prefer to petition politicians
column2: show up at their offices like i did with @jeffflake today
column3: and do volunteer work and advocacy with victims.  the way rape culture has been created and assaults erased has never been easy.  now
column4: i’m reading and hearing comments about “innocent until proven guilty
column5: ” which only applies in court proceedings
column6: not the equivalent of a job interview.  i am hearing about false accusations (which account for 2-5% of the actually reported rapes). it’s all very triggering and makes me want to banshee-wail at the world and never have the daughter of my dreams.  instead: i say to all of my sisters (and brothers): i believe you.  i will always believe you.  i stand with you.  and thank you @chromeo for using your power for something good and standing with us.  your comment to me today about bravery soothes some of the rage-pain i’ve been feeling.

328604;instagram;2018-09-27 23:47:20;FALSE;this has been an extremely difficult day, not only for dr. ford, who heroically testified about an incredibly traumatic event in front of the world, but for so many women and men who have been victims of sexual assault. watching ford's testimony, it reminded me of moments in high school, where so many of us learn about sex and relationships, where i was repeatedly objectified, groped and laughed at by entitled, over-priviledged white males who thought my body was theirs for the taking and theirs to comment on. i've been thinking about those boys, who are now all grown up, who i see on ig from time to time, who've probably never had to answer for what they've done. i can only hope today's testimony, and our current conversations on sexual assault in light of the #metoo movement, have influenced some of those men to think about their behavior, really look at it, and realize how wrong and damaging it was. but for now, my heart goes out to all of you who may have had a difficult time today. i stand with you. #ibelievechristineblaseyford;;en;#metoo, #ibelievechristineblaseyford;;;;;0;;stephdubick;Stephanie column1: 328634;instagram;2018-09-28 18:48:15;FALSE;"the man who raped me paid for half of my plan b the next day. he handed me a crumpled handful of bills and said
column2: ‘because it takes two to tango’ and i thanked him profusely. then went and threw up in the bathroom at work. he gave me thirty four dollars.

column1: the devastation of being raped was not in the violence of the physical act for me. it was in the realization that i could be seen as a body without a soul. that what was inside of me was unrecognizable— undesired
column2: worthless. that the man who raped me could not see my heart breaking as i realized that my trust was misplaced. the understanding on a base level that i could never be loved by him. maybe not by anyone. that i was not seen. that i was no one.

column1: that is the most crushing version of loneliness. to be unseen and unrecognized and used until something inside you breaks. to understand fully
column2: into the deepest part of yourself
column5: you will never be more than a paper doll in their life story. i stayed silent because i couldn’t
column7: explain the hole in my heart that was left from that realization. the unbearable reality of the world we live in was brought to light and i didn’t want to believe it. .

column1: because it doesn’t take two to tango. .
while the man who raped me paid good money for a dance
column2: like i was a monkey with cymbals
column3: i witnessed the destruction of my very self
column5: that i do not mean anything to that man. there was no place for me or my humanity inside of him. and now i have to face that there is also no space inside our government
column7: inside of our culture and society. keeping yourself silent hurts less than being silenced by others
column8: but your spirit pays the same price.

column1: believe it or not that price is greater than thirty four dollars.

column1: the truth is we will never truly know what actually happened.

my intuition tells me this man is lying - he has more to hide and is desperately (and feebly) attempting to conceal the truth of his choices.  there is more to this story than a ""little bump and grind."" the truth is there is a serious problem in society.  it goes beyond polarities of politics
column2: it goes beyond dogma of religion.  it goes beyond all of this.

column1: there is a problem when anyone holds a belief system (their b.s.) that nudges them towards getting something over on someone else.  reaching out to take what is not theirs to hold.

this is a ""micro"" snapshot that is so representative of the larger cosmic game at play.  we need to have the courage to speak out about this (and all atrocities that are not aligned with 9th consciousness)
column2: which what we are seeing here is just a manifestation of the life state of animality.  the three lower life states (hell
column4: animality) are weaving a web of a three-d existence - the time has come for this to crumble
column6: evolve.  we are witnessing timelines that have gone on in a ""same shit

column1: 328667;instagram;2018-09-28 21:39:18;FALSE;"spilling my guts like this abandoned piano (selfie i shot on my way home from therapy yesterday). tw: sexual assault trauma.

sending all my love & power to everyone reliving their trauma due to everything playing out on the world stage re: sexual assault. over the last year we've been experiencing the same bittersweet pain of the #metoo movement. of course there is liberation knowing we are not alone & that survivors of sexual assault are finally being heard
column2: but i cannot deny the extreme pain
column5: & anxiety that floods me at the same time. trauma is so incredibly complex & so hard to understand. so many people are quietly reliving their trauma by force & being expected to function normally - at times it feels inescapable. yesterday i closed out an emdr session with my therapist which dealt directly with my own rape
column6: the events that led up to it
column7: & the indescribably painful fall out from it all - & how it dictated many of my own toxic/negative behaviors & mindsets that i have been working very hard to free myself from. i had become a prisoner of my own pain. with the help of my gifted therapist and emdr
column8: over time i've been able to re-wire the feeling patterns & mindsets that the event(s) had etched into my heart & mind — from beliefs of “i am alone & abandoned
column16: & i forgive myself.” i feel free
column19: but that doesn't mean i'm not still suffering. remember: healing is not linear. to all survivors out there ~ i fucking love you. you are not alone. you are whole. you are so strong. you deserve to be treated with love & respect
column23: and validated. you deserve to be protected & taken care of - supported. i am here with you. if you ever want to talk
column24: if ever want to chat about emdr therapy for healing through past trauma (of any sort)

column2: but i cannot deny the extreme pain
column5: & anxiety that floods me at the same time. trauma is so incredibly complex & so hard to understand. so many people are quietly reliving their trauma by force & being expected to function normally - at times it feels inescapable. yesterday i closed out an emdr session with my therapist which dealt directly with my own rape
column6: the events that led up to it

column1: i was told that if i said anything that he’d say it was my fault
column2: and i started to believe him. i was only 12
column3: i didn’t know any better and any little self confidence i had was gone. .

column1: i’d wake up to him naked next to me in my bed
column2: i’d be grounded for 8 weeks at a time only for him to be able to lock me in his bedroom when my mom was gone for work. he’d whisper to me that if i ever said anything
column3: i’d be the one in trouble. and i believed him. he was my step dad
column4: a guardian i was told i could trust. it left me confused on how i saw myself
column5: who i could trust and i grew up struggling with my own sexuality. .

column2: i told my mom and she chose to not believe me
column3: my whole family doubted me. i was questioned constantly as the teenage rebel who just wanted freedom. yes they were right
column4: i wanted freedom; but not in the ways they assumed. i wanted to break free from the cage i had built around myself to guard my heart. whether they believed me or not
column5: i wasn’t going to allow this to conquer me

column1: i tried to call the cops
column2: after a night of him and my mom fighting i jumped out of a 2 story window and ran away to my dads. i told the police everything from my childhood till then and they said they’d be in touch. they told me they would do a follow up with him and i; 3 days later him & my mom were gone
column3: no where to be found. and i had never heard from the police again
column4: i’d call get put on hold but never any call back or follow through. i lived my entire teenage life in fear that he’d come kill me like he said he would if i ever told a soul

column1: he recently died from stage 4 emphysema
column2: now as i would never wish harm on anyone
column3: i felt in a way it was karma doing justice. but when he died the feeling of guilt for feeling free was overwhelming. it was and still is a feeling i have a hard time understanding. .

column1: scream it out of your body sisters.
until you have startled and surprised yourself with the register and power of your own voice.

column3: breathing in air that is wrought with eons of trauma

column1: the foulness and putrid stench of a rotting society and civilization has been aired out for all of us to smell. -
the odor you sniff makes it hard to breathe cleanly
you know of the heaviness that i speak.
the rancid aroma of ancient waste
column3: mingled with your hopes and desires

column1: you know of what i speak.

column3: and scream into the enveloping fold of night. you want to pierce the sound of silence with the sharpest tip of your sword.

column1: scream and screech and holler and yell.
probably more than once if you are ready to tell the truth.
you may have attempted to scream out before.
but your screams were zippered up behind straight-jackets and lies. behind threats and persuasion and rationale and obedience and fear and trauma and powerlessness.
i know you would have screamed if you could.
i know many of you did.
i know many of you have cried today
your scream is still there sister.
waiting for you to call her out
column3: from the bench where she waits patiently for you.

column1: scream for the cement in their veins.
this energy has got to get cleared out sister. trust in me today. i am here to steeer you home to yourself.
if the woods and a pair of bare feet are not possible
column2: use your pillow and a closed door.

column1: your rage and your fire and your presence on the earth are a holy trinity. -
i want to hear you scream sister.
i want to hear us all scream ourselves clean from shame
i am with you my beloveds.

you know of the heaviness that i speak.
the rancid aroma of ancient waste
column3: mingled with your hopes and desires

column1: you know of what i speak.

column3: and scream into the enveloping fold of night. you want to pierce the sound of silence with the sharpest tip of your sword.

column1: scream and screech and holler and yell.
probably more than once if you are ready to tell the truth.
you may have attempted to scream out before.
but your screams were zippered up behind straight-jackets and lies. behind threats and persuasion and rationale and obedience and fear and trauma and powerlessness.
i know you would have screamed if you could.
i know many of you did.
i know many of you have cried today
your scream is still there sister.
waiting for you to call her out
column3: from the bench where she waits patiently for you.

column1: scream for the cement in their veins.
this energy has got to get cleared out sister. trust in me today. i am here to steeer you home to yourself.
if the woods and a pair of bare feet are not possible

column1: your rage and your fire and your presence on the eah are a holy trinity. -
i want to hear you scream sister.
i want to hear us all scream ourselves clean from shame
i am with you my beloveds.

column1: 328679;instagram;2018-09-28 21:25:34;FALSE;"my father taught me to fear men.
from a very young age i was educated about rape
column2: about the horrors that could happen to young girls and women. about how men are not to be trusted.

column1: i was taught how to physically defend myself just in case and would run with my dad with the lesson to learn how to never give up if someone is chasing me.

my father didn’t teach me to be quiet and obedient. he taught me to scream and fight and to never stop…until it’s over.  quite the opposite of what society teaches women. he taught me as if these types of situations were inevitable.  instead of being an innocent little girl
column2: i learned about rape and prepped to go to battle for my body.

column1: he instilled a fear and a super hyper-vigilance in me i’ve carried through my life.
that fear didn’t keep me from receiving cat-calls
column5: though. it didn’t free me from people saying to me “oh just let him look
column7: he deserves it” or the “you’re leading me on wearing that”. none of it is ok.

column1: women walking around in fear of men and always remaining super hyper-vigilant is not ok.
women taking the blame for “ruining” someone’s life who already ruined theirs is not ok!
society making women feel like all they are is a body they should feel shame for is never ok!
they are taking their bodies and their power back.
the feminine warrior is rising in women and we are saying no more!
to all the women. i hear you. i see you. and i stand with you!

column1: i am far from comfortable with telling my story... i am 28 years old and have only told a few people over the years

#whyididntreport… because i was a child. because i didn’t realize until years later what had actually happened to me. because i was afraid. because i am still afraid. because it makes me uncomfortable.

i am so disheartend in seeing people say or share things about how these women’s “claims” can’t be true due to the amount of time that has passed without “reporting it”…. how this is a “witchhunt”... ""how that poor man”""…. let me just say that most woman never report their assault/abuse. ever.

column2: i am not comfortable telling my story… but what i will share is
column3: if my abuser was up for a position that was a life term in the highest court of our land in which his character played the biggest role in his duty
column4: i would feel obligated to speak up and tell my truth. i’m only speaking up now in hopes that my friends and family who have this mindset
column5: that it couldn’t be true because it’s been 30+ years or that this is a witch hunt
column6: ect…. it has been 20+ years for me and i haven’t spoken or reported it and i will continue on doing that for now… i am not brave enough to speak my truth like dr. ford. the courage this woman has
column7: is courage i dream about everyday. she is a hero. she is my hero. for anyone
column8: but especially woman who say this woman isn’t telling the truth should be ashamed of themselves… and just know
column9: when you say this woman isn't telling the truth or share things mocking this or are supporting kavanaugh.. you are the reason woman don't speak out.

to help women through of the most physically trying and vulnerable experiences of the human condition.  have you ever seen absolute terror in someone’s eyes ? or a scream that makes your heart sink.  trust, labor + delivery nurses can decipher different screams, the sound a mother makes when she’s lost her baby, versus the sound she makes crowning unmedicated and then there’s another scream.  the sound a women makes when the birth of her baby triggers the memory of previous assault or rape is like nothing else in this world.  it will break your heart and shake you to your core.  sometimes the triggering occurs when they get an epidural and suddenly being immobilized reminds them of being attacked or restricted.  pure fucking panic and fear in the truest sense that cannot be feigned.  that’s why #survivors never forget.  because even if they have blocked it out emotionally, their body and brain remembers.  sometimes a history of sexual abuse or assault will be noted in someone’s chart and sometimes we will randomly see this particular behavior and know that even though she might not disclosed that information that something must have happened to her.  that’s how specifically horrifying it is to be a survivor.  you can get therapy and be in a loving relationship and about to start a family and that is stolen from you because on what should be the best day of your life, you remember the worst moment of your life.  these are crimes against humanity.  those who commit them must be held accountable.  i don’t care how long it’s been, i don’t care what men were like then or what they are currently like, i don’t care who was drunk or not.  if you force a person to commit a sexual act, attack or grope them- it’s wrong.  to the women who defend these men, wake the fuck up. column1: 328736;instagram;2018-09-28 21:19:09;FALSE;"@regran_ed from @iamnataliebrite -  i remember being told it was ok for a man to speak & act sexually inappropriately toward me “because he has a good heart & doesn’t mean anything by it”. -
i remember having an old gm tell me “there’s nothing i can do” after i told him one of his managers was sexually harassing me. -
i remember a boy in highschool sneaking into my tent & putting his tongue in my mouth while i was sleeping

i remember being put in countless situations where it took me time to realize just how fucked up it truly was. maybe because i didn’t want to see it. maybe because the pain of facing it was worse than the pain of forgetting it. -
i didn’t realize i had a voice
column2: choice or an option to say no. -

column1: i remember not saying anything because “he was my friend”
column3: or because “he didn’t mean anything by it”. -

column1: the weight of all that has made me & us feel unseen
all the times we have been made to feel like nothing more than a body. -
all the times that made me believe that because i was a woman i had to be “good
all that made me believe that it was ok for a man to degrade me
column4: or treat me like an object. -

column1: all the times that taught me how to downplay or make excuses for the inexcusable. -
all the moments that taught me to make light of this ugly ugly shadow. -
i am more than this body.
i am more than what this body can give or do for you. -
i refuse to keep biting my tongue
column3: or fear going places by myself. -

column1: i refuse to continue feeling like i cannot walk at night or go through a parking lot without putting my keys in my hands as a weapon
maybe that’s what we need now though. -
maybe that’s actually what we are seeing & doing. -
all the souls of every women past present & future waking up

column7: or hate on my nose. it internalizes to her that women hating themselves is normal.

column1: 328740;instagram;2018-09-28 21:19:43;FALSE;"it’s time to have a talk. i have always been transparent with you all on here and on twitter so if you don’t follow me on twitter
column2: i’m about to say what i said last night. •••••

column1: i don’t want sympathy i just want my story to be heard. i want to explain #whyididntreport and to let people know that they are not alone. •••••
it’s been 17 years since the last time i was sexually abused. yes the last time. it happened not once
column3: multiple times. i was 6 when it started. it happened wherever my uncle could get me alone. family party with too many people? let’s skip it today. babysitting me? perfect alone time! and it kept happening because i was too young to know that what was happening was wrong. and then after that when i did realize what was going on
column4: i became strong and told him to fuck off. i felt shameful and held it in for years to come. 7 years to be exact. when i finally came out with it... no one believed me except my parents
column6: and grandma. i’ll have you know i have a large family. for that many people to not believe me broke me. how do you not believe someone??? how?? what did i have to lose except my entire family??? •••••

column1: the worst was when we were on a family vacation to bethany beach and my family was upstairs playing cards and i had to use the bathroom but someone was upstairs. i went downstairs really fast and he trapped me in a bedroom on the lower floor. locked me in. i screamed. •••••

no one heard me. i cried. my dad asked why i was upset when i went back upstairs. i told him i fell. he asked to see my legs to check for bruising (i have anemia so ice is my best friend). no bruises. he didn’t question it. next day i wanted to go back to the house from the beach but it was a far walk so my parents didn’t want to bring me back so my uncle offered. i said no it’s okay i’m fine here and they were like you made a big fuss now go. what was i supposed to do? i went and when i was showering he entered the bathroom and well
column2: i don’t even have to say what happened next because it’s not pretty. •••••

column1: 328748;instagram;2018-09-28 21:06:23;FALSE;"this. matters. her story matters. sexual assault and sexual discrimination does and always will matter. no matter who you are in our society. we may still live technically in a “man’s world” as they say but each step forward does make a difference and is finally chipping away at their reality. no character or dignified grace means you do not belong in power. times are changing for the better because we are uniting
column2: connecting and sharing our stories that we believe will help make a difference for all. believe and don’t give up. we all have stories that unfortunately are relatable but are worth sharing and which helps. now is the time. thank you to all of your courage and strength and to #drchristineblaseyford for being who she is
column4: sharing her pain and having a whole community behind her
column5: inspired by her strength and courage after all these years. we are never alone. ❤️❤️💪🏾🙏🏽 .

328751;instagram;2018-09-28 21:07:14;FALSE;"this is what a woman that has been raped looks like... .
would you have ever guessed she was sexually assaulted by seeing this photo? probably not. just because we don’t physically see someone being sexual assaulted
column2: does not mean it did not happen. .

column1: last year my wife was sexually assaulted in riverside ca. it happened 4 months after i proposed to her
column2: and went to court and faced her assailant 1 month after our wedding day. no one knew what we went through the last year and a half. no one knows of the long crying nights
column6: and triggers that we dealt all while trying to “host” a wedding. yesterday i watched dr. fords testimony of her sexual assault and i felt her pain since my wife has experienced sexual assault her self. and to hear the way kavanaugh and the senator respond is fucking disgusting. sexual assault is not something that happens one night and you forget about it. it completely changes your life
column7: and will be part of your life till you die. some days it’s like day 1 all over again. the memories are vivid
column9: police station is still chillingly cold
column11: small actions and memories are intense triggers. when she was assaulted
column12: i couldn’t even hug or comfort my wife because her clothing and fingernails had evidence that the police needed to collect
column13: and me comforting her would be tampering evidence. this is our story from a normal wednesday night turned into a nightmare.

column1: we don’t want pity. we want awareness for sexual assault. if you have been a victim of sexual assault. please speak to someone you trust or seek a therapist that specializes in sexual assault. my wife has done therapy every week since her assault
column2: and it has helped her more than anything.

column1: we cannot allow this to keep happening.
if you know someone that is a victim of sexual assault
column2: please be a friend to them and ask them how they are really doing. sharing is healing. men
column3: thank you for doing your part to protect woman and give them a shoulder to cry on or a ear that’s willing to listen.

column2: and went to cou and faced her assailant 1 month after our wedding day. no one knew what we went through the last year and a half. no one knows of the long crying nights
column6: and triggers that we dealt all while trying to “host” a wedding. yesterday i watched dr. fords testimony of her sexual assault and i felt her pain since my wife has experienced sexual assault her self. and to hear the way kavanaugh and the senator respond is fucking disgusting. sexual assault is not something that happens one night and you forget about it. it completely changes your life
column7: and will be pa of your life till you die. some days it’s like day 1 all over again. the memories are vivid
column9: police station is still chillingly cold
column11: small actions and memories are intense triggers. when she was assaulted
column12: i couldn’t even hug or comfo my wife because her clothing and fingernails had evidence that the police needed to collect
column13: and me comfoing her would be tampering evidence. this is our story from a normal wednesday night turned into a nightmare.

column1: we don’t want pity. we want awareness for sexual assault. if you have been a victim of sexual assault. please speak to someone you trust or seek a therapist that specializes in sexual assault. my wife has done therapy every week since her assault
column2: and it has helped her more than anything.

column1: we cannot allow this to keep happening.
if you know someone that is a victim of sexual assault
column2: please be a friend to them and ask them how they are really doing. sharing is healing. men
column3: thank you for doing your pa to protect woman and give them a shoulder to cry on or a ear that’s willing to listen.

328752;instagram;2018-09-28 21:07:35;FALSE;consensual sex should never feel unclear
after posting about my ""grey area"" sexual assault experience i had many women privately and not so privately reach out to me about their own experiences that were similar
it's sad how common it is
sexual assaults that feel a little like a ""grey area"". let me make one thing clear.... when consent wasn't given it's not a grey area
just because it was someone you were dating
just because it was a friend you trusted
just because you both had been drinking doesn't excuse a lack of consent
you either consented or you didn't
i remember the first time i had consensual sex
column2: i was making out with my boyfriend and he stopped and asked me if i wanted to have sex. he didn't just take my pants off and shove himself into me. which is a common confusing area for young women to navigate

column1: but i wanted to kiss him and fool around and so it was just a misunderstanding and of course he thought it was okay to start having sex with me even though i didn't want to.""
well i had been flirting with him all night and i led him on.""
trust that icky feeling in your gut in these situations
1) always assume the answer is no. if you're too shy to ask someone if they want to have sex you're not mature enough to have sex in the first place so put your pants back on
column2: bud. absolutely do not assume it's okay to shove yourself into another person

column1: 2)when someone else is wasted don't have sex with them.. period
column2: like at all. if they can't function clearly enough to walk
column3: they can't function clearly enough to think about if they actually want to have sex with you. have enough self confidence to know you don't have to prey on someone in a vulnerable state to get sex

column1: 3) communicate. empower yourself around your sexuality and talk about it. if you don't want to do something say no. saying no to sex (or anything you don't want to do) doesn't make you lame
column3: or a bitch. you don't owe anyone an explanation. if you're not sure what someone is okay with

column1: 328756;instagram;2018-09-28 21:08:06;FALSE;"""anger is loaded with information and energy..anger expressed and translated into action in the service of our vision and our future is a liberating and strengthening act of clarification
column2: for it is in the painful process of this translation that we identify who are our allies with whom we have grave differences
column3: and who are our genuine enemies.

column1: every woman has a well-stocked arsenal of anger potentially useful against those oppressions
column3: which brought that anger into being. focused with precision it can become a powerful source of energy serving progress and change. and when i speak of change
column4: i do not mean a simple switch of positions or a temporary lessening of tensions
column5: nor the ability to smile or feel good. i am speaking of a basic and radical alteration in those assumptions underlining our lives."" source: audre
column7: sister outsider: essays & speeches by audre lorde(berkeley: crossing press

column3: i was an apprentice training on a tour in europe when my drunk superior blocked my way out of his hotel room
column4: placed his hand on my waist
column5: and pressed my body against the wall trying to kiss me as i dodged out from under him. afterwards
column6: my boyfriend at the time would tell me it was my fault for being in that room to begin with (it wasn’t). and the long story of me not reporting the harassment
column8: only to realize that i may as well have not reported it because so little was done...well
column9: this is one you’ve heard before. my experience—and it isn’t the only one
column10: just the one that has stuck with me most recently—is tame compared to what dr. christine blasey ford went through. what deborah ramirez and julie swetnick and countless other women have gone through. i don’t have any solutions and it’s easy to feel hopeless
column12: lately. but i believe these women. all women. the courage and poise i saw during dr. ford’s testimony shook me
column13: honestly because i would have lost my shit on that stand. i’m so exhausted by all of this. ‘the rape of proserpina

column5: and a democratic socialist. jeff flake is not my favorite person and we don't see eye to eye on many things
column6: but i think he is a good man at heart. in all things
column7: i try to be objective and fair and i think i do pretty well.

column2: this picture is worth noting. i first saw this yesterday and i wasn't the only person to note that jeff flake looks pained. the two men on either side of him are not actually listening to dr. ford. they're waiting to respond/hear others respond. they don't have a trace of emotion on their faces.

column1: jeff flake is listening to her. really listening. he's letting himself feel the full weight of her words
column2: and i think it's safe to assume he didn't know his picture was being taken in this moment. he has the same look on his face that i did. that look is empathetic pain. it's unmistakable. in midst of all these men trying to discredit and attack dr. ford
column3: jeff flake appeared to be one of the few who heard what she had to say with an open mind and a sympathetic heart.

column7: he'll no longer be a judge.
