column2: after i’d been sexually abused repeatedly for a year by the same man. it carried on for another year. ▫️ 2nd photo is me celebrating the @patriots xlix victory
column3: a week before i was raped. ▫️ 3rd photo is me 2 weeks after
column4: on an impromptu trip to la to heal. ▫️ then my #metoo post
column5: which i believe is more important now than ever to share again. i can’t say i didn’t report
column6: because i did. but only because of the fantastic boys in my life who brought me to the er. i was denied a rape kit by a female doctor. my detective made me sign a form claiming i wasn’t raped so she could close the case. i live life looking over my shoulder with a knife in my back pocket. ▫️ “violence against women” is no longer simply against women - it never has been. throughout my ordeal the most support i received was from the men in my life
column7: and a male vice detective. as much as men can be terrifying and patriarchal
column8: they are human. women can cause more harm than good at times

column2: isn’t it - this patriarchy problem. sharing again an essay i wrote “since when did we start looking like sluts?” based on the first slutwalk london protest in 2011. features bare-breasted women with no apology from me. it was first published on sojournposse.com
column3: and republished on @medium in 2015. i thought it would sink quietly to the bottom of the internet drawer
column4: but no. recently it caught new attention again on @medium in the light of #metoo and the 2017 women’s march. this essay was written from a visual culture perspective
column5: informed by anthropology research by @salinachristmas. for those who are new to my observations on the female body topic - hello! my photography work on the female body was peer reviewed by ucl’s opticon 1826. i took a step back from  this observation to focus on work within the tech industry
column6: and guess what - there’s sexism in stem too. i’m the kind of creative that dislike to be pigeonholed by my gender. my work as a designer is genderless. however it’s quite evident now wherever i look
column7: patriarchy is still raring it’s ugly head. child marriage is still legal in some countries and pussy grabbers still get elected as presidents. hopefully this article will give you peace through understanding of what we see and where we stand in the society. i’ll try to write more essays in the future. peace out.

column1: 328781;instagram;2018-09-28 19:48:32;FALSE;well...here it goes. warning ⚠️ graphic. don’t read this post if you find abusing young girls or women offensive to your beliefs.••••i will begin with a question. do the current leaders of our country have any awareness about the fury of energy they are about to release? kali rising is here. goddess warriors have united. there will be a revolution in this country that has been like no other in american history. why? because women are finally standing up and speaking their truth and resisting the toxic status quo.••••i
column3: have been sexually assaulted. in 1987 i was outside a party in high school talking to a boy when he blocked me between himself and a car and began groping me and trying to pull my pants off. he waited until no one was around. i told him repeatedly i was on my period to get him to back off. he quickly discovered i really was on my period and then proceeded to tell me how disgusting i was. my own blood saved me. honestly
column4: i would have kicked his ass if he went any further because i was a fighter. i had to be after living with all forms of abuse from my stepfather and abandonment from my father. fighting back was my weapon of choice because it was the only voice i had at that time in my life.••••this boy went back to school the following week and told his groupies horrible things about me. i survived because i had thick skin but i despised that prick with all of my being. when i told a girlfriend about what had happened that night she told me that he had raped her. she kept it all to herself because she was so afraid of not being believed and she was terrified of the repercussions. she came from a well known and upstanding family in the community and she was more worried about what her parents would think about her! this is the culture we live in. it’s beyond heartbreaking because for every story like mine there are thousands and millions more. ••••what is happening in our politics will have devastating effects on all women and young girls living in america. the message is loud and clear. men are allowed to rape and abuse women and women are not allowed to tell their stories

column9: i would have kicked his ass if he went any further because i was a fighter. i had to be after living with all forms of abuse from my stepfather and abandonment from my father. fighting back was my weapon of choice because it was the only voice i had at that time in my life.••••this boy went back to school the following week and told his groupies horrible things about me. i survived because i had thick skin but i despised that prick with all of my being. when i told a girlfriend about what had happened that night she told me that he had raped her. she kept it all to herself because she was so afraid of not being believed and she was terrified of the repercussions. she came from a well known and upstanding family in the community and she was more worried about what her parents would think about her! this is the culture we live in. it’s beyond heartbreaking because for every story like mine there are thousands and millions more. ••••what is happening in our politics will have devastating effects on all women and young girls living in america. the message is loud and clear. men are allowed to rape and abuse women and women are not allowed to tell their stories

column1: 328784;instagram;2018-09-28 20:50:53;FALSE;"this has been an extremely difficult couple of weeks for the people out there who have had to relieve traumas in light of the kavanaugh hearings.
i've seen people - including our own president - question why christine blasey ford would not have come forward sooner if this was true.
i was young the first time it happened. i had never had sex before. was it meant to be forceful? did it matter if i had said i wasn't sure
column2: that i had cried? i didn't outwardly say no. i wasn't attacked
column3: or dragged into an alley way. it wasn't so bad. everyone would think i was a slut

column1: the second time i was a little bit older. i was so drunk i didn't know it had happened until someone brought it up cautiously afterward. ""why did you do that?"" everyone had watched. i couldn't answer. i didn't know. i was so embarrassed. why did i let myself get that drunk? i hadn't fought back. did that even count?
the third time i was dating someone who had been unfaithful to me. i stayed with him but didn't feel comfortable sleeping with him. i woke up one  night to him on top of me
column2: having pulled my pants down in my sleep. i tried to push him off
column3: and i sobbed. ""it's not fair"" he told me sternly. was i being unreasonable? he was my boyfriend
column4: so did it matter? i still cared about him and didnt want to ruin his life

column2: i went to pick up some things i had left at the house of a man i had been dating
column4: as he was verbally and physically abusive. i had been afraid to get my things
column5: but it would be a quick trip
column6: and he seemed fine with it. he turned off the light and pushed me onto the bed. i told him no
column7: and tried to get up. he was a lot stronger than me. he pushed me back down again and pulled of my clothes
column8: ripping them in the process. i just kept saying no. ""stop being difficult
column9: he told me. ""you know you want it."" eventually i burst out into tears and couldn't stop. he immediately became angry
column11: and left the room. he had always been dominant during sex
column12: and i had encouraged it. was this just a misunderstanding
column13: a miscommunication? was it my fault for coming here when i knew how he was?

column1: fact people who have been sexually assaulted don’t come forward right away.  hell many men/women don’t ever come forward. the reason that is
column2: is because the world we live in makes victims feel like it’s their fault for what happened to them so they keep their mouth shut and try to move on with their life the best they can. it took me 6 months to tell my mother and local law enforcement about my assault in 2012 i was 17 when it happened and knew the guy for many years. i was scared
column4: confused.. going over every detail blaming myself.  by the time i came forward i had no witnesses
column5: and no evidence. it was a he said she said situation. i couldn’t bring myself to wear a wire to try and get the person to confess. i couldn’t bring myself to talk to my rapist and get a confession. so that was it  for me nothing ever happened case closed. i still had to go to school and see his face
column6: i still had to go to class and sit across from him reliving everything. thought about ending everything. it’s so hard for victims to just get over it. it’s so traumatizing people don’t understand how traumatizing a assault has on someone. what’s going on right now with christine ford is really hitting home with me. it’s disgusting how people are so quick to call her a liar because she never came forward until now. it’s so god dam hard to come forward. it doesn’t become easier in time to come forward it almost feels harder to come forward after so much time has passed. 6 years later and i still cry over it. it’s shameful how people treat the victims. so here’s a big fuck you to anyone who says “well there’s no police report so it must not have happened” “boys will be boys” “ he’s young let’s not ruin his life” “did you say no?” “did you scream?” “are you sure that really happened?” #metoo #ibelievechristineblaseyford";;en;#metoo

column6: i still had to go to class and sit across from him reliving everything. thought about ending everything. it’s so hard for victims to just get over it. it’s so traumatizing people don’t understand how traumatizing a assault has on someone. what’s going on right now with christine ford is really hitting home with me. it’s disgusting how people are so quick to call her a liar because she never came forward until now. it’s so god dam hard to come forward. it doesn’t become easier in time to come forward it almost feels harder to come forward after so much time has passed. 6 years later and i still cry over it. it’s shameful how people treat the victims. so here’s a big fuck you to anyone who says “well there’s no police report so it must not have happened” “boys will be boys” “ he’s young let’s not ruin his life” “did you say no?” “did you scream?” “are you sure that really happened?” #metoo #ibelievechristineblaseyford";"wrong!

column2: does not mean it did not happen. last year my wife was sexually assaulted in riverside ca. it happened 4 months after i proposed to her
column3: and went to court and faced her assailant 1 month after our wedding day. no one knew what we went through the last year and a half. no one knows of the long crying nights
column7: and triggers that we dealt all while trying to “host” a wedding. yesterday i watched dr. fords testimony of her sexual assault and i felt her pain since my wife has experienced sexual assault her self. and to hear the way kavanaugh and the senator respond is fucking disgusting. sexual assault is not something that happens one night and you forget about it. it completely changes your life
column8: and will be part of your life till you die. some days it’s like day 1 all over again. the memories are vivid
column10: police station is still chillingly cold
column12: small actions and memories are intense triggers. when she was assaulted
column13: i couldn’t even hug or comfort my wife because her clothing and fingernails had evidence that the police needed to collect
column14: and me comforting her would be tampering evidence. this is our story from a normal wednesday night turned into a nightmare.

column1: we don’t want pity. we want awareness for sexual assault. if you have been a victim of sexual assault. please speak to someone you trust or seek a therapist that specializes in sexual assault. my wife has done therapy every week since her assault
column2: and it has helped her more than anything.

column3: thank you for doing your part to protect woman and give them a shoulder to cry on or a ear that’s willing to listen.

column1: 328837;instagram;2018-09-28 20:54:35;FALSE;"the solitude following sexual assault is paralyzing
burying your battered body in a cave of shame
your mouth has been clamped shut
by friends and peers telling you that your experience was not enough
this kind of thing happens at parties by design
since he was the popular kid
that it was all your choice
but our experiences will not be in vain
hoping others feel empowered in theirs
knowing that they don’t have to live life

column1: i grew up in a different era. not the era of #metoo- the era of silence. i didn’t know about @taranajaneen (tarana burke ❤️) when i was in my teens. i read an article about fiona apple disclosing on the internet
column2: found a chat room i posted in once. i knew a world of silence
column3: i knew a world of alone.

column1: that world was dangerous for me. i didn’t want to be in it.

column2: i realized that the brief therapy i had gone too
column3: all the truces i had made with myself and my history and what/who had hurt me
column4: had ceased to be really effective. like #christineblaseyford
column5: i had convinced myself that i should just get on with my life and not disclose. (because most women/gnc/male-identified survivors don’t disclose
column6: so we can presume most survivors are having a similar conversation with themselves.)

column2: and i don’t want to be too much.” i spent three more months realizing i could not live in that world. if i wanted to continue to 30
column3: i’d have to choose me over my silence.

column1: i chose my own way. i wrote myself out of it. i wrote a 300-page book about a survivor of childhood sexual abuse who takes the reins on her own life by stealing the ashes of the man who assaulted her
column2: going on a cross country road trip for answers.

hardly anyone gets to ask questions of the person who abused them; almost no one gets answers. (see: yesterday 🤬) dealing with my trauma has largely been realizing there are some answers i’ll never get.

column1: resonate with you?? i wrote this book for us.
writing was hard. it felt arduous and loud and
column4: by putting stinging ointment on all my scars.

column1: i can’t imagine what it would’ve been like if i broke my silence with

column2: with talking to men and not to my friends
column3: with talking to politicians and not to an empathetic crowd.

column2: i grew up in a different era. it was codified that i should accept shame as a bedfellow. it was expected that i should look at underage photos of myself and think “was i asking for it there?” my silence was honored. look; what a good girl. seen and not heard.

i believe this is a conversation worth having. while i support and advocate and phone bank and march and sign and live a life that believes in justice
column3: ""where does peace fit in to the conversation?"" i've determined after years of research that it doesn't - but that shouldn't suggest that it should remain that way.

column1: there's a reason the politicians committed to upholding the status quo never even utter the word ""peace"". if they started a conversation on peace
column2: who would play their game of right and wrong? they wouldn't stand a chance.

column1: what we have witnessed in the kavanaugh hearing has been a sham. a show. and a stain on the democratic process. but peace...peace does not depend on courts and elected or selected officials. it circumnavigates the tension between right and wrong completely. just like compassion and empathy
column2: peace cannot be argued. true peace cannot be ""wrong"" nor can one ""fight"" for peace. it subverts the paradigm completely. i can't help but feel that it is for this very reason that peace is so often ignored. if it can't swing the pendulum of conversation from ""right"" to ""wrong"" or from left to right
column3: what's the use in talking about it? i'll tell you why - because peace does not depend on broken systems. peace starts with us. the people. and there is nothing stronger or scarier than the people united for peace. and that's my vision for us all - that we see peace as a fire that doesn't just burn. it dances! that we don't just struggle to ""stay woke
column4: but that we heal as a people

column1: we all have a role to play and it is my opinion that our allyship counts whether we are typing away on our computers
column3: or just holding our children close. may this be a wake up call to us all that the conversation on peace cannot be pushed aside any longer.
and subscribe to peace made public on instagram

column1: 328879;instagram;2018-09-28 20:48:42;FALSE;"i penciled a beautiful strong minotaur woman a while back when i felt a bit under the weather.  horned deities have been demonized through out cultures for political reasons
column2: despite their roots in agriculture and farm based religions. what was once a symbol of abundance
column3: strength and being able to feed our young was turned into a symbol to justify too many tragedies to count. too many people ripped from their lands and rights
column4: silenced for political gains. of course this is a topic for another time
column5: but hearing about the kavanaugh situation yesterday reminded me to finish her and post her message.

column2: doubt or fear silence you. we all breathe the same air
column3: many of us experience the same trials in life. no matter what you face
column4: you are never alone. your strength can never be taken away from you
column5: no matter what others would like you to believe. stand in your truth
column6: and know you are understood and loved unconditionally by the people who have shared your pain.

column1: personally i believe her; i can not express the grief i feel for everyone who has gone through this pain and for everyone who feels undervalued because of the decisions made yesterday. stand tall
column2: be proud of who you are
column3: never let anyone silence you or make you feel less than. remember that you are not victims; you are victors; heroes

column1: 328883;instagram;2018-09-28 20:49:07;FALSE;"i wish i had the phone number for the therapist i saw in college. i wish i could call to tell her about how often i thought of her and our conversations in the last 48 hours. i was assigned to her randomly & i hated her at first. i wanted her to tell me how to make it better. that’s what therapists do
column2: right? give advice & make you feel better?! i resented her for quite some time for asking me all those questions. they felt like the same questions over & over
column3: and she never gave me advice. i was frustrated during the sessions and exhausted after. i flaked a couple times because i didn’t see the point. i just wanted my life back…just tell me how to do it

column1: what i didn’t know was that she was preparing me for the beautiful
column2: empowered life i have now. she guided me gently with her questions until i cracked
column3: then she asked me the questions and gave me the tools to help me heal myself. and there is nothing stronger than someone who knows how to self-heal.

column1: you have to feel all the hurt
column2: all the anger. cry until you shake. feel broken. the good news? you’re not broken. you’re only bent. and when you’re bent you get to see another perspective. and the other side is brilliant. the scars throb sometimes (like now) but you learn to find the light. you know the light is always there and it’s going to be ok
column3: even when you don’t feel ok (which is ok too). there is so much power in this.

column1: the last two days have been reflective for me. i’ve gone on lots of walks; beyond grateful for a spectacular colorado fall. i thought about posting something to encourage the women i know are hurting to reach out to me. because it never really goes away
column2: does it? even for the bold
column3: strong ones. but the truth is
column4: i didn’t post anything because…i ultimately cannot help you. i can be there for you
column7: but i cannot mend what you grieve over. no one can. only you can heal you.

column1: i can still smell the room. the room where my healing began. where a compassionate
column3: licensed professional guided me through my journey. a journey 13 years in the making. there is hope

column2: all the anger. cry until you shake. feel broken. the good news? you’re not broken. you’re only bent. and when you’re bent you get to see another perspective. and the other side is brilliant. the scars throb sometimes (like now) but you learn to find the light. you know the light is always there and it’s going to be ok
column3: even when you don’t feel ok (which is ok too). there is so much power in this.

column3: strong ones. but the truth is
column4: i didn’t post anything because…i ultimately cannot help you. i can be there for you
column7: but i cannot mend what you grieve over. no one can. only you can heal you.

column1: 328884;instagram;2018-09-28 20:49:08;FALSE;"this kavanaugh hearing is indeed a national disgrace. •
because i absolutely believe it’s time we err on the side of a woman’s right not to be violated. •
the fact that we’re willing to put yet another man on the supreme court whose innocence is not beyond doubt
column2: simply because the people who support him believe he’ll vote the way they want him to
column3: is yet another dismissive slap to the face of every woman everywhere who has ever been forcefully aggressed upon by a man. •

column2: not a criminal trial. kavanaugh doesn’t go to jail if he isn’t appointed to the supreme court over this. •

column1: he actually keeps his current job and just doesn’t get promoted to one of the most powerful positions in the world. •
i don’t say this as a democrat. because i’m not a democrat.
i am simply a man who understands the time has come when nothing less will do than a fundamental shift in the way we orient ourselves towards women. •
it’s time we stop treating women’s experiences as mere inconveniences or obstacles to the outcomes we want. •

column1: 328909;instagram;2018-09-28 20:39:49;FALSE;"i believe that rape culture is harmful to everyone.
i believe that saying ""boys will be boys"" is as demeaning to boys as it is to girls.
i believe that telling women to smile more is telling them that they should be a part of your scenery and that their inner experience is less important than your aesthetic.
i believe that no sexual assault was ever prevented by a woman wearing a longer skirt.

i believe that forbidding transgendered individuals from using whatever restroom they choose takes the real threat of sexual assault and twists it to exert control over a group of people who are more likely to be survivors of assault themselves.
i believe that the ""what about...?"" argument is used to shut down one story without paying the respect due to either side of the narrative.

i believe that the future of those accused of sexual assault and harassment should not be prioritized over the future of those who experience it. i believe that learning to face the human consequences of your actions will not be more damaging than living with the memories of survival has been.

i believe that masculinity is not inherently toxic but that the stories in our culture today impart the lesson on boys and men that using your power to keep others down is the only way to keep your power.
i believe that there is a long road ahead before the stories of survivors are given the same consideration as the stories of those who stand accused.

column1: 328913;instagram;2018-09-28 20:40:19;FALSE;this is not about party or politics. it is about respecting the basic rights and dignity of women. i’ve been brought to tears by dr. ford’s testimony

column1: 328990;instagram;2018-09-28 20:24:48;FALSE;"**trigger warning** the first time it happened i was 11.
it doesn't happen like they say in the movies. it wasnt strange men being predators
column2: it was guys that i knew. i knew them
column4: hell i knew some of their girlfriends. the first time was at school. in the hallway. did anyone help me? nope. not even my school counselor. sadly
column5: the last 2 times i was so blackout drunk that there was no signs of struggle. no way of proving what happened to me.

column3: i stood in front of an entire courtroom full of strangers and had to tell
column5: what happened to me. essentially reliving my trauma. i was embarrassed. somehow i got it in my head that i did something wrong and that's why it happened to me.

column1: the 2nd time i was at my home bar
column2: with the same group of friends i always hang out with. he asked me to give him a ride home (which i was not sober enough to be doing) and when we got there i asked to use his restroom. i was going in and out of conciousness but remember waking up on the cold bathroom tile with him on top of me. i remember trying to push him off of me and trying to yell but he put his hand over my mouth and was way too heavy to push off.

column1: the 3rd time i was in my bed. in my safe space after a night out drinking with friends. one of my friends walked me home and made sure i got there safe. my roommate however decided that was an opportunity for him to take advantage of me. i remember waking up the next morning alone in my bed thinking it was a bad dream...until i saw his clothes and shoes on the floor.
since the justice system failed me the first time
column2: i didn't even bother pressing charges the last 2 times. there was not enough ""proof"". dr ford may not remember every single detail. but she still deserves to be heard
column3: and the fbi should still investigate these allegations. this man is trying to get nominated into a position of power that he could serve for the rest of his life!

column1: im thankful for dr fords courage to stand up in front of everyone and share her story. i believe you and i stand with you as a sexual assault survivor.

column1: the 3rd time i was in my bed. in my safe space after a night out drinking with friends. one of my friends walked me home and made sure i got there safe. my roommate however decided that was an oppounity for him to take advantage of me. i remember waking up the next morning alone in my bed thinking it was a bad dream...until i saw his clothes and shoes on the floor.
since the justice system failed me the first time
column2: i didn't even bother pressing charges the last 2 times. there was not enough ""proof"". dr ford may not remember every single detail. but she still deserves to be heard
column3: and the fbi should still investigate these allegations. this man is trying to get nominated into a position of power that he could serve for the rest of his life!
